New Hope for India
Cambridge, USA—India's latest election may be the most significant positive economic event since 2014.
Indian voters decisively rejected the Indian National Congress, which had ruled India almost continuously since its independence from Britain in 1947.
They may come to appreciate this decision.
Sonia Gandhi, the widow of former Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi and leader of the Congress Party, has been effectively running the party since 1998, while Prime Minister Singh was merely a puppet.
Under her leadership, the Congress Party pursued a populist agenda, increasing transfer payments, which led to India's annual economic growth rate falling below 4% in 2013.
Per capita GDP still hovers around $4,000, less than half of China's.
Newly elected Prime Minister Narendra Modi promised during his campaign to bring rapid growth in employment and income across all of India, similar to what he achieved when he served as Chief Minister of Gujarat.
Under Modi's leadership, Gujarat became a business-friendly state, expanding economic activity and attracting business investments from both within and outside India.
A significant feature of the latest election was that Modi's Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) secured an absolute majority in the National Parliament, which can be considered an unprecedented achievement in India.
Therefore, Modi does not need to compromise with other national or regional parties in order to pursue his legislative agenda.
Two key officials will assist Modi in his economic plan.
The newly appointed finance minister, Arun Jaitley, has extensive political experience and has held ministerial positions in previous BJP governments.
Jaitly is also known as a strategic thinker sympathetic to business interests.
Raghuram Rajan will continue to serve as the Governor of the Reserve Bank of India (central bank). Rajan is an outstanding economist, and during his tenure as Governor of the Reserve Bank of India, he showed a desire to reduce India's double-digit annual inflation rate and attempted to reform some inherent productivity constraints in the Indian financial sector.
The measures needed to stimulate economic growth will take time to be implemented and produce results.
But if you want to know whether the new government is taking action to achieve faster long-term growth, you should examine whether progress has been made in the following ten policy areas.
Education.
Although India has outstanding higher education and technical institutions, only a small portion of the population can access the opportunities these institutions offer, because primary and secondary education in India is very backward.
Only 60% of Indian adults have literacy at the primary school level.
The teachers themselves have inadequate education and lack motivation; many teachers never even show up at the schools where they are supposed to teach.
Infrastructure.
India needs better roads and ports to efficiently transport products across the country and around the world.
The recent expansion of private airlines and airports shows that the private sector can also play a role in this area.
Fiscal integration.
Large budget deficits absorb national savings that could otherwise be used to expand business investment. Budget deficits lead to an increase in national debt that can only be financed through future taxes.
Privatization.
The manufacturing and other industrial enterprises owned by the Indian government are often inefficient and frequently result in the consumption of national savings.
Selling these enterprises directly helps accelerate economic growth.
Eliminate subsidies.
Power and energy subsidies have led to wasteful overconsumption and increased fiscal deficits.
Although these subsidies are politically difficult to remove, they should be replaced with cash transfers. Currently, India has a relatively efficient cash transfer system due to the implementation of a new fingerprint-based cash transfer system.
Agricultural reforms.
Under the current system, the government purchases, stores, and distributes agricultural products.
The result is large quantities of goods stockpiled in warehouses, while production incentives are distorted.
The agricultural market should be privatized.
Property rights and zoning.
As long as you have been to Mumbai or other major Indian cities, you will see that zoning restrictions lead to poor land use in urban areas, constraining development.
Unclear property rights, especially agricultural property rights, hinder industrialization in rural areas.
Relaxing foreign investment restrictions.
Currently, foreign enterprises cannot become controlling shareholders of banks and insurance companies.
Relaxing these restrictions could strengthen the financial sector and play an important role in economic growth.
Tax reform.
India's complex national and state sales tax system distorts domestic trade.
The debate over replacing these taxes with a national value-added tax and adopting a revenue-sharing system has been going on for a long time, and it is now time to move to the implementation phase.
Corruption.
Major corruption cases among the elite have undermined economic confidence and hindered official decision-making.
India is also deeply affected by small-scale corruption, and bribery has become a common feature of all business and personal transactions.
The government should severely punish high-level corruption and restrict small-scale corruption through a new cash transfer system.
Driven by expectations of stronger growth and increased profits, India's stock market has risen 20% this year.
Now, Modi and the BJP need to prove to the world that they can fulfill their election promises.
